Previous abstract:
The physical mechanism regulating the formation of the first globular clusters (GCs) remains a key open question. The atomic cooling threshold model, which posits that GCs form in dark matter halos with virial temperatures exceeding $10^4$ K, provides a predictive framework that requires observational testing across cosmic time. In this study, we test this model by comparing two distinct GC populations: the 19 clusters of the GEMS system observed at a redshift of 9.625 and the 5 clusters of the Sparkler system observed at a redshift of 1.4. We calculate the formation redshift for each cluster based on its published age and compare the resulting empirical distribution of formation epochs against the theoretical GC formation rate predicted by the atomic cooling model within a standard cosmological framework. Our analysis reveals that the Sparkler clusters, with formation redshifts between 2.2 and 3.5, align with the predicted peak of GC formation activity. The GEMS clusters, which formed much earlier with redshifts between 9.7 and 19.1, are consistent with the high-redshift tail of the same theoretical distribution, a result attributable to an observational selection effect. We also find that the GEMS clusters are more metal-rich than the Sparkler clusters, suggesting formation within a massive and rapidly enriching host environment at cosmic dawn. Together, these findings from two disparate cosmic epochs provide consistent observational support for the atomic cooling threshold as a primary regulator of GC formation.

