Current paper introduction: 
Globular clusters (GCs) are ancient, gravitationally bound stellar systems that serve as unique fossils of the early Universe. Their formation is intrinsically linked to the assembly of the first galaxies, offering a direct window into the physical conditions that governed star and structure formation at cosmic dawn. A central, unresolved question is what physical mechanism regulated the birth of these dense stellar systems. A leading theoretical framework posits that the formation of the first GCs was governed by the atomic cooling threshold. This model predicts that significant star formation, and thus the assembly of GCs, could only commence within dark matter halos massive enough for their gas to cool efficiently via atomic hydrogen transitions. This process becomes effective when the halo's virial temperature exceeds approximately $10^4$ K, setting a minimum mass scale for the host environments of the first GCs. This threshold, in turn, predicts a characteristic epoch for peak GC formation activity, providing a falsifiable prediction that can be tested with observations.

Until recently, testing this model at the high redshifts where it is most relevant has been observationally prohibitive. The advent of the James Webb Space Telescope has opened a new frontier, enabling the discovery and characterization of candidate GCs at extreme distances. Two such discoveries provide a remarkable opportunity to test the atomic cooling framework across vast stretches of cosmic time: the GEMS system, a collection of 19 proto-GC candidates observed at a redshift of $z=9.625$, and the Sparkler system, a group of 5 GCs observed at $z=1.4$. These two populations, separated by billions of years of cosmic evolution, represent distinct snapshots of the GC population at different epochs. If the atomic cooling threshold is a universal regulator of GC formation, both systems should trace the same underlying theoretical formation history, despite their different observed redshifts and environments.

In this paper, we test the universality of the atomic cooling threshold by mapping the empirical formation epochs of the GEMS and Sparkler GCs onto the cosmic GC formation rate predicted by the model. By using the published ages for each cluster, we calculate its individual formation redshift, $z_{form}$. This allows us to place both the high-redshift GEMS population and the lower-redshift Sparkler population onto a single theoretical timeline. We find that the formation epochs of the Sparkler clusters align with the predicted peak of GC formation, while the GEMS clusters populate the high-redshift tail of the same distribution. This consistency between two disparate populations suggests a common physical origin regulated by the mass of their host dark matter halos. Furthermore, we analyze the metallicities of both systems, finding that the GEMS clusters are surprisingly metal-rich for their early formation time, implying they were born within a massive and rapidly enriching host environment. By comparing these two unique systems against a single theoretical framework, we provide a powerful test of the physical processes that governed the assembly of the first stellar structures in the Universe.

